10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Barbell strategy</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It feels like there are two dominant retail in=
vestment strategies:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Buy and hold index funds, or</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Actively trade individual stocks and, whil=
e you=E2=80=99re at it, maybe options or crypto.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Many ordinary people=C2=A0do not want to think=
 about their investments much, and modern finance has designed a product th=
at is ideally suited for them. It is the index fund (or index exchange-trad=
ed fund), whose essential thesis is that thinking about investments is unne=
cessary and in fact bad, and you should just buy the market and save on cos=
ts.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Other people, though, do want to think about t=
heir investments, and they want to think about investments that are fun to =
think about: stocks (or options or crypto) that are volatile, stocks of com=
panies that do fun or interesting or world-changing things, stocks of compa=
nies with charismatic and entertaining chief executive officers, meme stock=
s.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is not=C2=A0<em>much=C2=A0</em>in betwee=
n. In particular, the whole industry of active mutual fund management is bu=
ilt on the idea that, if you don=E2=80=99t want to manage your investments,=
 you can pay someone else to do it for you. But that idea feels pass=C3=A9 =
in 2023. These days, if you don=E2=80=99t want to manage your investments, =
the accepted approach is to pay someone else almost nothing to almost not m=
anage them for you: An index fund will do almost no managing and charge alm=
ost no fees, and that is widely considered the=C2=A0<em>optimal=C2=A0</em>a=
pproach. And if you want to manage your investments, you want to manage you=
r investments; you want to pick fun stocks, not hire a star mutual fund man=
ager to do the stock picking for=C2=A0you.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Where does that leave the active mutual fund m=
anagers? Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Silla Brush and Loukia Gyftopoulou report that=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33116434.256422/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjMtMTAtMjIvYWN0aXZl=
LXZzLXBhc3NpdmUtaW52ZXN0aW5nLW1vbmV5LW1hbmFnZXJzLWNvbmZyb250LWVuZC1vZi1idWx=
sLW1hcmtldD9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDIzMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV=
9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEwMjMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1Z=
mY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8b7fc51c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  things are bad for them</a>=
:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Across the $100 trillion asset-management indu=
stry, money managers have confronted a tectonic shift in investor appetite =
for cheaper, passive strategies over the past decade. Now they=E2=80=99re f=
acing something even more dire: The unprecedented run of bull markets that =
buoyed their investments and masked life-threatening vulnerabilities may be=
 a thing of the past.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">About 90% of additional revenue taken in by mo=
ney managers since 2006 is simply from rising markets, and not from any abi=
lity to attract new client money, according to Boston Consulting Group. Man=
y senior executives and consultants now warn that it won=E2=80=99t take muc=
h to turn the industry's slow decline into a cliff-edge moment: One more be=
ar market, and many of these firms will find themselves beyond repair. =E2=
=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More than $600 billion of client cash has head=
ed for the exits since 2018 from investment funds at T. Rowe, Franklin, Abr=
dn, Janus Henderson Group Plc and Invesco Ltd. That=E2=80=99s more than all=
 the money overseen by Abrdn, one of the UK=E2=80=99s largest standalone as=
set managers. Take these five firms as a proxy for the vast middle of the i=
ndustry, which, after hemorrhaging client cash for the past decade, is tryi=
ng to justify itself in a world that=E2=80=99s no longer buying what it=E2=
=80=99s selling. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a slow but surely declin=
ing trajectory,=E2=80=9D said Markus Habbel, head of Bain &amp; Co.=E2=80=
=99s global wealth- and asset-management practice. =E2=80=9CThere is a scen=
ario for many of these players to survive for a few years while their asset=
s and revenues decline until they die. This is the trend in the majority of=
 the industry.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Cheery!=C2=A0What do you do about this? One ap=
proach is to get into some adjacent=C2=A0business that does not rely on sto=
ck-picking; Abrdn =E2=80=9Ccut the business into three parts: a mutual fund=
 business, a wealth unit that also serves retail investors and a platform f=
or financial advisers =E2=80=94 a strategy that has yet to prove it=E2=80=
=99s working.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other approach is for active managers to g=
et out of liquid easily indexed public markets and into something else. Abr=
dn has also =E2=80=9Clargely abandoned competing in large-cap equity funds,=
 choosing instead to emphasize small-cap and emerging-market strategies.=E2=
=80=9D And of course there is private credit:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For many other firms, private markets =E2=80=
=94 and, specifically, the private-credit craze =E2=80=94 are now the lates=
t perceived savior. Almost everyone, from small to giant stock-and-bond hou=
ses, is piling into the asset class, often for the first time. In the past =
year and a half, a surge in M&amp;A in the space has been driven by such ho=
uses, including Franklin, that are eager to offer clients the increasingly =
popular strategies, which typically charge higher fees. Others have been po=
aching teams or announcing plans to enter the space.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI think that=E2=80=99s a big driver f=
or many of these firms =E2=80=94 they look at their own financials and thin=
k about what=E2=80=99s going to keep us afloat over the next few years,=E2=
=80=9D Amanda Nelson, principal at Casey Quirk asset-management consultancy=
 at Deloitte, said in an interview.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CJust buy all the stocks=E2=80=9D is a=
 cheap and easy investing strategy that is also endorsed by academic resear=
ch, but =E2=80=9Cjust make private loans to all the buyouts=E2=80=9D sort o=
f obviously doesn=E2=80=99t work. So there is room for investment selection=
, and fees, there.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile at the Wall Street Journal, <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33116434.256422/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9maW5hbmNlL3N0b2Nrcy93aG8teW91LWNhbGxpbmctZHVtYi1tb25leS1l=
dmVyeWRheS1pbnZlc3RvcnMtZG8tanVzdC1maW5lLTlkZDYzODkyP21vZD1ocF9sZWFkX3Bvczg=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2b0d870a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Hannah Miao reports</a> that a=
ctually retail stock-picking works great:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wall Street has long derided amateur investors=
 as unsophisticated market participants, prone to buying high and selling l=
ow. But the typical individual investor=E2=80=99s long-term mindset and pen=
chant for risk-taking has proved fruitful in the technology-driven market o=
f the past decade, defying the =E2=80=9Cdumb money=E2=80=9D caricature.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The average individual-investor stock portfoli=
o has risen about 150% since the beginning of 2014, according to investment=
 research firm Vanda Research, which began tracking the data nine years ago=
. That beats the S&amp;P 500=E2=80=99s roughly 140% during the same period.=
=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some of this is about stock selection: Recent =
years have been good for the stocks that retail investors tend to like.</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The typical small investor holds a=
n outsize position in megacap tech companies. Apple, Tesla and Nvidia alone=
 make up about 40% of the average individual=E2=80=99s stock portfolio, acc=
ording to Vanda. Although big tech stocks plunged last year, those investme=
nts have dominated the market for most of the past decade and have helped f=
uel the S&amp;P 500=E2=80=99s 10% advance this year.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But some of it is apparently behavioral: Indiv=
idual investors can be more contrarian than professionals can.</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One advantage small investors have over profes=
sionals: They don=E2=80=99t have to worry about reporting performance to cl=
ients. That helps some individuals feel comfortable riding out market downt=
urns. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Everyday investors are known to buy the dip, p=
iling into markets during weak periods. Many jumped into stocks in March 20=
20 when the market plunged at the onset of the Covid-19 pandemic, and rode =
the high as shares rebounded.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Crudely speaking, if index funds offer market =
performance, and retail investors on average outperform the market, then pr=
ofessional investors on average will underperform the market: =E2=80=9COver=
 the past decade, about 86% of all large-cap U.S. equity funds have underpe=
rformed the S&amp;P 500, according to S&amp;P Dow Jones Indices.=E2=80=9D</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This seems bad for the big asset managers? The=
y are squeezed from both sides: There is the rise of indexing, but there=E2=
=80=99s also the pretty good performance of individual investors who pick t=
heir own stocks. For a long time now, one argument for active management ha=
s been along the lines of =E2=80=9Csure index funds look good in a rising m=
arket, but wait until the market goes down; then people will see the value =
of active stock selection.=E2=80=9D But in fact people have seen the value =
of owning a lot of Apple and Tesla, which they can just do on their own. Th=
e real argument for active management surely has to be something like =E2=
=80=9Csure index funds=C2=A0and also individual stock trading look good in =
a market dominated by the biggest names, but wait until Tesla and Apple und=
erperform and the way to make money is by buying stocks that retail investo=
rs have never heard of.=E2=80=9D Which is a harder pitch.</p>
