<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When I was a young mergers-and-acquisitions la=
wyer in New York, someone told me that, when you do a merger in=C2=A0German=
y, everyone has to get together and=C2=A0<em>read the entire contract out l=
oud=C2=A0</em>before signing it. This struck me as wild.<a class=3D"footnot=
e-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; =
display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0<em>Our=C2=A0</em>merger agreements were so long and boring, and =
I could not imagine reading them out loud.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand the actual practice of corpo=
rate lawyering in New York is a little rickety too, in a way that might ben=
efit from spending four hours reading the contract out loud to each other. =
Here is roughly how a corporate contract is negotiated:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">One side=E2=80=99s lawyers write=C2=
=A0the contract in Microsoft Word and email=C2=A0it to the other side=E2=80=
=99s lawyers as an attachment.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Tho=
se lawyers summarize it for their clients, get feedback, and =E2=80=9Cturn=
=E2=80=9D the contract, writing in all of their proposals in Word and email=
ing it back to the first side with a redline.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">The first side=E2=80=99s lawyers get the contract back, summari=
ze the changes for their clients, and turn it back with their counter-propo=
sals.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This continues for a while, =
with each redline being a bit less red.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: =
5px;">Eventually the contract is close enough that each side=E2=80=99s lawy=
ers print out a signature page =E2=80=94=C2=A0just the last page of the con=
tract, with page number 71 or whatever printed on it, with a signature bloc=
k for the client to sign =E2=80=94=C2=A0and hand it to their client. The cl=
ient signs it and scans it and sends the PDF back to the lawyers.</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">At like 3:47 a.m., one side=E2=80=99s lawye=
rs email the draft contract in Word to the other side=E2=80=99s lawyers say=
ing =E2=80=9CI think this is final,=E2=80=9D and the other side=E2=80=99s l=
awyers email back =E2=80=9Clooks good, here are our signature pages,=E2=80=
=9D attaching the PDF, and the first side=E2=80=99s lawyers email back =E2=
=80=9Chere are our signature pages, congratulations.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The most junior associate uses Acrobat to make =
a PDF of the final contract and combine it with the signature pages, so the=
re is one PDF containing the official signed contract. Then she sends it ou=
t to everyone else, though they are all in bed by this point.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Probably nobody ever reads that final PDF.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This always troubled me. In law school you thi=
nk that there is =E2=80=9Ca contract,=E2=80=9D that it is a piece of=C2=A0<=
em>literal paper</em>=C2=A0signed in ink by two human beings sitting in a r=
oom with each other, and that if there is a dispute about what the contract=
 says you can just get it and open it. But in actual high-stakes corporate =
contracts, there are like 40 different Word versions that exist only as att=
achments to emails between junior law firm associates, attachments that pro=
bably even they didn=E2=80=99t read. The=C2=A0<em>signature=C2=A0</em>means=
 nothing; it=E2=80=99s a blank page that someone signed and handed to the l=
awyers before the contract was agreed. If there is a dispute about what the=
 contract says, you have to go back through the email chain to pick out whi=
ch attachment everyone thought they were signing off on.=C2=A0The dispute w=
ill likely take the form =E2=80=9Cwe signed off on the 2:12 a.m. version an=
d did not realize that you made changes to the 3:47 a.m. version that you d=
id not flag to us.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If the final step of this process was for the =
lawyers to say =E2=80=9Clooks good, let=E2=80=99s get some sleep and then m=
eet up in the morning to read the whole thing out loud,=E2=80=9D some misun=
derstandings might be avoided.</p>
