=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 a <em>Bloomberg Green</em> story</a> about how Occidental Petroleum Corp. =
built =E2=80=9Ca mega-plant for carbon capture and storage =E2=80=A6=C2=A0i=
nto a natural gas processing plant=E2=80=9D; the project was called Century=
. But:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A=C2=A0<em>Bloomberg Green</em>=C2=A0investiga=
tion has revealed that Century never operated at more than a third of its c=
apacity in the 13 years it=E2=80=99s been running. The technology worked bu=
t the economics didn=E2=80=99t hold up because of limited gas supplied from=
 a nearby field, leading to disuse and eventual divestment. Oxy quietly sol=
d off the project last year for a fraction of the build cost. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It might seem, from a climate perspective, lik=
e a boon that Century never reached its full potential since its performanc=
e was inextricably linked to natural gas production. But picking the wrong =
location for an expensive carbon capture project carried real climate costs=
. Cheaper shale gas elsewhere met the same demand, without the benefit of c=
arbon capture. As a result, total emissions likely ended up higher.</p>
</blockquote>
